rinking vessels of ancient Athens in their thousands. Against the background of revelry for which these vessels were produced, this volume presents a comprehensive interpretation of the colourful world of the images. These range from mythical tales about the god of wine, to the lecherous activities of the half-human Satyrs and complex rituals of intoxication and ecstasy. The results shed light on the many-sided image of Dionysos in classical Athens, as well as on the forms of interaction between image and viewer.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aDionysusc(Greek deity)xCult. 0aDrinking vesselszGreecezAthensxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aIdols and images in art. 0aIdols and imagesxWorship. 0aSatyrs (Greek mythology) 0aSatyrs (Greek mythology). 4aAttic Vase Painting. 4aDionysos. 4aIconography. 4aIkonographie. 4aSymposion. 4aattische Vasenmalerei. 7aART / History / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070100508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2016z9783110485097oZDB-23-DGD0 cEPUBz97831103905060 cprintz978311022223440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311022224140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110222241423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110222241.jpg  a978-3-11-070100-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGDb2016  aZDB-23-DGGb2016